  "prompt": "Is it true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime?",
  "response": "No, it is not true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime. While chickenpox (caused by the varicella-zoster virus) is a common childhood illness, not everyone contracts it. Here are a few reasons why:\n\n1. **Vaccination**: The varicella vaccine, introduced in the mid-1990s, has significantly reduced the incidence of chickenpox. Many people who receive the vaccine never develop the disease.\n\n2. **Natural Immunity**: Some individuals may be exposed to the virus without developing symptoms or may have a mild case that goes unnoticed, leading to immunity without a full-blown infection.\n\n3. **Limited Exposure**: Not everyone is exposed to the virus, especially in areas where vaccination rates are high and the disease is less prevalent.\n\n4. **Boosting Immunity**: People who have been vaccinated or previously infected may have boosted immunity if exposed to the virus again, preventing a second infection.\n\nWhile chickenpox is highly contagious, it is not an inevitability for everyone, thanks to vaccination and other factors.",
